---
import CalculatorLayout from "../../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro";
import { CdnRequestCostCalculator } from "../../components/calculators/CdnRequestCost";
import { DataEgressCostCalculator } from "../../components/calculators/DataEgressCost";

const title = "CloudFront Cost Calculator (bandwidth + request fees)";
const description =
  "Estimate CloudFront cost from bandwidth delivered and request pricing, with room to model blended regional rates, traffic spikes, and the request mix that often distorts CDN bills.";
---
<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/calculators/cloudfront-cost-calculator"
  intro="This CloudFront cost calculator helps you estimate two common CDN line items: bandwidth and requests. Plug in your own $/GB and $ per 10k assumptions, then add them to get a monthly estimate."
  examples={[
    "Bandwidth: 10,000 GB/month at your $/GB + Requests: 400M/month at your $ per 10k -> estimate monthly CDN cost.",
    "If your workload has many small objects, request fees can become a meaningful part of the bill.",
  ]}
  includes={[
    "Bandwidth estimate from GB/month and $/GB pricing assumptions.",
    "Request-fee estimate from requests/month and $ per 10k pricing assumptions.",
  ]}
  excludes={[
    "Origin egress and cache fill costs (model separately if billed).",
    "Tiered pricing by region unless you use a blended rate or model scenarios.",
  ]}
  how={[
    "Total = bandwidth cost + request fees.",
    "Bandwidth cost = GB/month x $/GB.",
    "Request fees = (requests/month / 10,000) x $ per 10k.",
    "If pricing is tiered, use a blended rate or run multiple scenarios and sum.",
  ]}
  faqs={[
    {
      q: "Is this an official CloudFront quote?",
      a: "No. It's a planning estimate based on the assumptions you enter. Always confirm pricing tiers, regions, and units in the official documentation.",
    },
    {
      q: "What inputs do I need?",
      a: "Monthly GB delivered to users and monthly request volume. If you only have throughput or RPS, convert them using the Units Converter and RPS-to-monthly tool.",
    },
  ]}
  lastUpdated="2026-02-23"
  related={[
    { href: "/calculators/cdn-cost-calculator", label: "CDN cost calculator (generic)" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-cloudfront-pricing", label: "Guide: CloudFront pricing" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-cloudfront-cache-hit-rate", label: "Guide: cache hit rate and origin egress" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-cloudfront-invalidation-pricing", label: "Guide: invalidation pricing" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-cloudfront-logs-cost", label: "Guide: CloudFront logs cost" },
    { href: "/guides/cdn-request-pricing", label: "Guide: CDN request pricing" },
    { href: "/guides/cloudfront-vs-cloudflare-cdn-cost", label: "CloudFront vs Cloudflare cost" },
    { href: "/guides/origin-egress-vs-cdn-bandwidth", label: "Origin egress vs CDN bandwidth" },
    { href: "/calculators/cdn-origin-egress-calculator", label: "CDN origin egress" },
    { href: "/calculators/unit-converter", label: "Units converter" },
    { href: "/calculators/rps-to-monthly-requests-calculator", label: "RPS to monthly requests" },
  ]}
>
  <div class="prose">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">1) Bandwidth</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      Use monthly GB delivered by the CDN edge to end users. If you start from Mbps charts, convert Mbps to GB/month
      using the Units Converter.
    </p>
  </div>
  <DataEgressCostCalculator
    transferLabel="CDN bandwidth (GB / month)"
    priceLabel="CDN price ($ / GB)"
    defaultGbPerMonth={10000}
    defaultPricePerGbUsd={0.06}
  client:load />

  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2>2) Requests</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      If your provider bills per request (often per 10k or per 1M), estimate monthly requests and apply the rate.
    </p>
  </div>
  <CdnRequestCostCalculator client:load />
  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">CloudFront cost is usually a two-line edge bill, but traffic mix decides which line hurts</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      This page is strongest when you treat CloudFront as two separate edge charges that happen together:
      <strong> bandwidth delivered to users</strong> and <strong>request volume at the edge</strong>. Many teams only
      watch one of them, then get surprised when request-heavy traffic or regional mix shifts move the monthly bill.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bandwidth</strong>: the edge-delivery line item that usually dominates media-heavy workloads.</li>
      <li><strong>Requests</strong>: the line item that grows faster on small-object, API-heavy, or bot-heavy traffic.</li>
      <li><strong>Origin side effects</strong>: separate from CloudFront itself, but often confused with it during reviews.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Where CloudFront estimates usually drift</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>One blended rate is used even though region mix changes materially across months.</li>
      <li>Average object size changes, so request fees and bandwidth stop moving together.</li>
      <li>Teams compare CloudFront edge charges to origin egress and accidentally double-count or undercount adjacent bills.</li>
      <li>Bot spikes and cache-busting releases increase requests faster than delivered GB.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What to review before trusting the CloudFront baseline</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Split edge bandwidth and edge requests into separate assumptions instead of forcing one blended story.</li>
      <li>Check whether your top regions need different effective rates.</li>
      <li>Review cache hit rate and invalidation habits before assuming request growth is purely user demand.</li>
      <li>Keep origin egress, log delivery, and invalidation-related work nearby, but not inside the same line item.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Baseline vs request-heavy CloudFront scenarios</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Scenario</th>
          <th>Bandwidth</th>
          <th>Requests</th>
          <th>Cache hit rate</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Baseline</td>
          <td>Expected</td>
          <td>Expected</td>
          <td>Current</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Peak</td>
          <td>High</td>
          <td>High</td>
          <td>Lower under surge</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>How to review the first real CloudFront month</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Check whether the miss came from regional rate mix, request growth, or origin-side leakage before rewriting the whole model.</li>
      <li>Compare edge bandwidth and edge requests separately against billing data so one driver does not hide the other.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:0">
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/">Guides</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/">All calculators</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-cost-calculator/">CDN cost calculator (generic)</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-cloudfront-pricing/">Guide: CloudFront pricing</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-cloudfront-cache-hit-rate/">Guide: cache hit rate and origin egress</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-cloudfront-invalidation-pricing/">Guide: invalidation pricing</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-origin-egress-calculator/">CDN origin egress</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</CalculatorLayout>

